@Node REQUIREMENTS "ScanHTML.guide/Requirements"

@{jcenter}@{b}Requirements@{ub}@{uu}

@{jleft}ScanHTML requires at least OS v37 (2.0 release).  You must know however that if used on a pre-v39 (3.0) machine, there is a bug in dos.library:  character-classes ([x-y]) are not converted properly to uppercase.  ScanHTML won't uppercase them either.  I suppose it will work OK if you use uppercase [x-y] patterns.  (See you AmigaDOS manual or dos.lib's autodocs about patterns)

The only other thing required is an HTML file. :)

@EndNode

@Node HISTORY "ScanHTML.guide/History"

@{jcenter}@{u}@{b}The Past@{ub}@{uu}
@{jleft}@{pari -4}@{lindent 4}
@{par}Version 0 Revision 1 - 16.8.1996 and before
Nothing recorded.
@{par}Version 0 Revision 2 - 21.8.1996
· Changed NOIMG to NOSRC.
· Now recognize tags not in uppercase
@{par}Version 0 Revision 3- 15.12.1996
· Now works when there's no '"'.
@{pard}@{lindent 0}

14.1.1997 - Since it seems stable, 0.3 is relabelled 1.0.  Also renamed ScanHTML (was ParseHTML).

@{jleft}@{pari -4}@{lindent 4}
@{par}Version 1.01 - 17.1.1997
· Fixed enforcer hit
@{par}Version 1.02 - 22.2.1997
· Replaced "NO#" argument with "STRIP#": The URL is truncated at the "#" instead of discarded.
@{par}Version 1.03 - 13.4.1997
· Now handle situations where an url is "." or "..".  In past, '/' was required (ie "./" & "../").
@{par}Version 1.04 - 15.4.1997
· Now complains about ".." followed by something else than nothing or than "/" but do not abort scanning.  This is a quick and dirty patch but I don't have the time to do more :)
@{pard}@{lindent 0}
